263678204176783.Text: I keep getting requests for me to post the story of how I met my wife on my Facebook page.  It is a pretty amazing story...it's like something you would expect to see in a movie. This post has absolutely nothing to do with politics, but for those of you who want to hear the story, here goes:  On May 25th, 2016 I stepped onto a tour bus in Rome, Italy. As I climbed up the stairs I looked up and saw an absolutely gorgeous girl sitting there looking down at me. I thought to myself, "This trip just got a whole lot more interesting!" and I sat in the seat in front of her. We talked for almost 4 hours on the bus that day and I was immediately hooked.   We toured all over Italy and I spent the majority of my time talking to Hannah. Five days into the tour we went to Pisa to see the Leaning Tower. It was pouring rain! I bought an umbrella from a street vendor and offered to share it with Hannah. The tour guide at Pisa asked if we were a couple and I joked that we were engaged before admitting that I had just met her a few days earlier. The tour guide embarrassed us in front of the whole group by saying that we obviously went together well and that we should become a couple. Little did I know that his comments prompted Hannah to consider a relationship with me.  I quickly figured out I had found the girl I wanted to spend the rest of my life with.  I also knew I only had 17 days to make her fall in love with me. One morning I asked to sit by her on the bus and virtually from that moment on we were always together.   We then travelled to Paris. We split off from the rest of the group and found some space by ourselves on top of the Eiffel Tower, and it was there I told her how beautiful she was for the first time. I asked a tourist to take some photos of us and I secretly bought an Eiffel Tower picture frame, put that picture in it, and gave it to her when we parted ways at the airport a few days later.  Once in London I took the subway until I found a flower shop. I bought her some long-stemmed roses and wrote her a note asking for her phone number. I left those items outside of her hotel room door a few minutes before she was heading down to supper. As you probably already guessed...I got the phone number!  Over the course of one year, I made 35 weekend trips to South Carolina to spend time with Hannah.  She was able to visit Alabama 5 times during that year as well, and she quickly fell in love with the area and the people who live here. On October 29th, 2016, I rented an airplane in Greenville, SC and flew Hannah back to Alabama.  I had secretly bought a ring and scheduled a photographer to be at the TVA Rockpile to capture the moment.  There, in front of the waterfall, I asked Hannah to be my wife.  Hannah finished out her teaching contract at Hidden Treasure Christian School in May 2017. We were married on June 30th, 2017 at her home church in Greenville, SC.  For our honeymoon, we returned to Venice, Italy and then cruised the Baltic Sea.

275271649875425.Text: Where do you live in Rib Mountain? If it is on one of 61 particular roads, whether the answer to that question will remain the same is still up in the air. Yesterday, the County petitioned the Wisconsin Supreme Court to review the decision of the Court of Appeals, which had reversed the circuit court in the Town's favor on whether the names of those 61 roads will have to change as part of the County's effort to implement a uniform addressing system.   So what did the Legislature do about it? Nothing. Should it have? Perhaps, since the one thing more than nothing is likely the legal bills. As a practicing lawyer myself, I have argued in the Court of Appeals and petitioned the Supreme Court for review. It's time consuming, tedious and expensive. In this particular case, it boils down to one simple word in the statute - "rural," and the question before the court is whether the county's statutory authority to implement a uniform addressing system extends beyond "rural" roads.   No one knows because the Legislature never defined the word. So define it. The issue has been weaving through the courts for well over a year and both sides deserve clarity. Getting it through the Legislature should not have been an issue because almost all counties in the state have gone through the process and could care less to go back, so it won't impact them. So why has it not been addressed - no pun intended? Easier to navigate the shoals that way. Just call it a local shooting match and move on.   Well, that is just not how I operate. Certain groups in Mosinee are likely happy to tell you I have upset them because something needs to be addressed and people elect you to take positions. If more than half disagree next time around, you're done and the next person is up. That is how I plan to represent the 86th starting in January.   My position on uniform addressing is this - some will agree; some will disagree; hence, my comments above. I would have talked to the County, then I would have talked to the Town, and I would have said to both I am going to put something on the table to define "rural" in hopes of saving everyone a lot of time, effort and legal expense. You folks give me some input, whether that is the US Census data, the Metropolitan Planning Organization documents or some other metric, and let's move forward.   Maybe it would have died in committee; maybe it would have been an easy rider to bill and saved everyone some time. Too late now. By the time of the next legislative session briefing in the Supreme Court will likely be done or wrapping up if it takes the case and the legal expense is done.   In the future, anytime there is an opening to save local governments in my district a headache, I plan to help while turning as much of the input over to them as possible. Vote August 14th. Thank you.
